 ($\\beta$) indices in the envelope of L1527 IRS. We find a rather\nflat $\\alpha \\sim$ 3.0 profile in the range 50-2000 au. Accounting for the\nenvelope temperature profile, we derive values for the dust emissivity index,\n0.9 < $\\beta$ < 1.6, and reveal a tentative, positive outward gradient. This\ncould be interpreted as a distribution of mainly ISM-like grains at 2000 au,\ngradually progressing to (sub-)millimetre-sized dust grains in the inner\nenvelope, where at R=300 au, $\\beta$ = 1.1 +/- 0.1. Our study supports a\nvariation of the dust properties in the envelope of L1527 IRS. We discuss how\nthis can be the result of in-situ grain growth, dust differential collapse from\nthe parent core, or upward transport of disc large grains.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Jun 2023 13:01:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-06-06"}
